# Instructions for Copilot

## Instructions for writing Python code

### Packages

- Assume that the packages NumPy, SciPy, and Matplotlib are available for use in the implementation of the code.

### Coding style and conventions

- Add NumPy-style docstrings to all functions you write, describing the purpose of the function, its parameters, and its return value.
- Follow PEP 8 style guidelines for Python code, including naming conventions, indentation, and line length.
- Use single quotes for string literals, and double quotes for docstrings.
- If the Ruff formatter is available, use it to format the code.

### Plotting

- When plotting with Matplotlib, save the output figures in PDF format.
- Save figures in the same directory as the code file, with descriptive filenames that indicate what is being plotted (e.g., `expected_utility_plot.pdf`).

### Vectorization

- Use vectorized NumPy operations if possible, but restrict vectorization to one dimension. Don't create hard-to-read code that involves np.meshgrid() or similar concepts, but instead use loops for the remaining dimensions.

### Running the code

- All Python code should be run using the Anaconda environment FIE463 to ensure that all relevant packages are available.
- DO NOT attempt to create the Anaconda environment or install packages yourself. Assume that the environment is already set up and ready to use.

### Git & GitHub

- DO NOT attempt to interact with the git repository in any way other than read-only operations, unless specifically asked to do so.
- DO NOT interact with GitHub (e.g., via the MCP server) unless specifically asked to do so.


## Language

- Use US English spelling and grammar.
- Use the Oxford comma when listing items in a sentence.
- Prefer bullet points with short sentences over long paragraphs in docstrings.
